  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you have a mortgage on the property you are selling, it needs to be formally discharged at settlement before the buyer can receive clean title. This is one of the more procedural parts of a sale, and most vendors only encounter it once or twice in their lives, so it is worth understanding what actually happens, who is responsible for what, and where delays commonly come from.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a mortgage discharge actually is</h2>
      <p>When you borrowed money to purchase your property, your lender registered a mortgage over the title at the Queensland Land Registry. This registration gives the lender a legal interest in the property as security for the debt. A mortgage discharge is the formal legal process by which that registered interest is removed from the title once the debt is repaid.</p>

      <p>Without a discharge, the title passes to the buyer with the lender's interest still recorded, which no buyer or their financier will accept. The discharge happens simultaneously with the payout of the loan at settlement, so the two events are coordinated through your solicitor or conveyancer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who initiates the discharge and when</h2>
      <p>You initiate the discharge by contacting your lender and requesting a discharge authority form, usually called a DA. Most major banks have online portals or dedicated discharge teams you can reach directly. Your solicitor or conveyancer will typically do this for you once you have a signed contract and an agreed settlement date, but it is worth confirming early in the sale process that your solicitor has lodged the request, because discharge lead times vary considerably between lenders.</p>

      <p>The discharge request should go in as soon as the contract becomes unconditional, not on the day you sign. This is one of the most common timing mistakes sellers make, and it is almost always the cause of settlement delays.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the solicitor coordinates with the lender</h2>
      <p>Once your solicitor has lodged the discharge authority, your lender will calculate the exact payout figure for your loan as at the settlement date. This figure includes the outstanding principal, any accrued interest, and the discharge fee. Your solicitor checks this figure against the settlement statement and confirms it is accurate.</p>

      <p>At settlement in Queensland, the buyer's solicitor, your solicitor, and the lender's representative (often via PEXA, the electronic settlement platform) all participate simultaneously. The sale proceeds flow through the PEXA workspace. Your lender's payout is deducted from the settlement funds before you receive the net proceeds. Once the payout is received and confirmed by the lender, the discharge is lodged electronically with the Queensland Land Registry and the title transfers to the buyer free of the mortgage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Typical discharge timeframes and what causes delays</h2>
      <p>Most banks will process a discharge authority within 10 to 15 business days of receiving it. Some of the major lenders, particularly during busy periods, can take three weeks or longer. Credit unions and smaller lenders can sometimes turn around a discharge more quickly, but this varies significantly.</p>

      <p>Delays typically come from three sources. First, the discharge authority being lodged late, often because the vendor did not realise they needed to initiate it separately from the sale process. Second, lender processing backlogs, which are more common in spring and in periods of high refinancing activity. Third, discrepancies in the payout figure, which can arise if a line of credit is secured against the same property or if there are multiple facilities attached to the mortgage.</p>

      <p>If a settlement delay is caused by the lender's failure to provide discharge paperwork on time, the buyer may be entitled to penalty interest, and your solicitor will need to negotiate an extension. This is frustrating but not uncommon, and it is almost always avoidable by lodging the discharge authority early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to the mortgage payout at settlement</h2>
      <p>Your lender does not receive a separate payment from you at settlement. Instead, your solicitor prepares a settlement statement that shows all the inflows (the purchase price) and outflows (the discharge payout, agent commission, legal fees, any adjustments for rates or body corporate levies) and calculates what is left for you.</p>

      <p>If the sale price exceeds everything owing and payable, the balance is deposited into your nominated account on settlement day, usually within a few hours of settlement completing. If you have a significant payout figure, for example on a property that has been heavily refinanced, the net proceeds can be materially smaller than the sale price, and it is worth working through the settlement statement carefully with your solicitor before settlement day so there are no surprises.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Discharge fees and how they appear</h2>
      <p>Lenders charge a discharge fee to process the release of their mortgage. This fee is set by the lender, not by law, and varies from roughly $150 to $600 depending on the institution. It will appear as a line item on your settlement statement, usually described as a discharge of mortgage fee or a loan payout fee. Your solicitor will have confirmed this amount with the lender during the payout calculation process.</p>

      <p>Some lenders also charge break fees if you are on a fixed rate loan and the sale triggers an early exit from the fixed term. Break costs are calculated on the difference between your contracted rate and current market rates, multiplied by the remaining loan balance and the remaining fixed term. On a large loan with a long fixed term in a falling rate environment, break costs can be substantial. If you are on a fixed rate loan, ask your lender for a break cost estimate as early as possible in the sale process so you can factor it into your net proceeds calculation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If you have multiple mortgages or a line of credit</h2>
      <p>If you have more than one loan facility secured against the property, all of them need to be discharged at settlement. This is common for sellers who have accessed equity through a line of credit or have refinanced and consolidated debts. Your solicitor will identify all registered interests on the title through a title search early in the conveyancing process and lodge discharge authorities for each one.</p>

      <p>A line of credit secured against your property is treated the same as a standard mortgage for discharge purposes. The outstanding balance at settlement date will be included in the payout figure and deducted from your sale proceeds. If you have been drawing on a line of credit and the balance is higher than you realised, review your current balance before settlement so the figure on the settlement statement aligns with your expectations.</p>

      <p>If you have a portable mortgage that you intend to transfer to your next purchase rather than discharge, this is possible with most lenders but requires a separate approval process and careful timing coordination with your solicitor. Portable mortgages need to be agreed with the lender well before settlement, not arranged at the last minute.</p>

